description: A trio of adult waterhens were found wading near the water among mangrove roots (the third waterhen was not captured in the picture). They might have been foraging for food. Sex indeterminate. The waterhen has white face and a yellow beak. It has dark slaty grey upperparts, which contrasts sharply with its white underparts. It's flanks, vent and undertail feathers are rufous-chestnut in color. It has yellow legs and feet.
Family of White-breasted water hen, other parent was about 5m away.

This juvenile individual of indeterminate sex was spotted amongst a patch of grass and shrub near a water body. It had black downy feathers, black beak, and a little bit of white that was only around the cheek region and near beak. These observations, coupled with the observation of an adult white-breasted waterhen near it, led me to think that it was a juvenile white-breasted waterhen. Other features observed included black feet and black iris.
